 away from poor black people turned ghettos and prisons into social pandemics. Americans in the North made this history. They tried to unmake it, too. Liberalism, rather than lighting the way to vanquish the darkness of the Jim Crow North gave racism new and complex places to hide. The twelve original essays in this anthology unveil Jim Crow's many strange careers in the North. They accomplish two goals: first, they show how the Jim Crow North worked as a system to maintain social, economic, and political inequality in the nation's most liberal places; and second, they chronicle how activists worked to undo the legal, economic, and social inequities born of Northern Jim Crow policies, practices, and ideas. The book ultimately dispels the myth that the South was the birthplace of American racism, and presents a compelling argument that American racism actually originated in the North.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxSegregationxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights movementszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh1 aPurnell, Brian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTheoharis, Jeanne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWoodard, Komozi40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479854318423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479854318.jpg  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK